If you draw random samples of size <m:math><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:math>, then as <m:math><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:math> increases, the random variable
<m:math><m:mi>ΣX</m:mi></m:math> which consists of sums tends to be <term target-id="normdist">normally distributed</term> and</para><para id="element-367"><m:math>
		<m:mo>Σ</m:mo>
		<m:mi>X</m:mi></m:math> ~
<m:math>
		<m:mi>N</m:mi>
		<m:mo>(</m:mo>
		<m:mi>n</m:mi>
		<m:mo>⋅</m:mo>
		<m:msub>
			<m:mi>μ</m:mi>
			<m:mi>X</m:mi>
		</m:msub>
		<m:mo>,</m:mo>
		<m:msqrt>
			<m:mi>n</m:mi>
		</m:msqrt>
		<m:mo>⋅</m:mo>
		<m:msub>
			<m:mi>σ</m:mi>
			<m:mi>X</m:mi>
		</m:msub>
		<m:mo>)</m:mo>
	</m:math></para><para id="element-603"><emphasis>The Central Limit Theorem for Sums</emphasis> says that if you keep drawing larger and larger samples
and taking their sums, the sums form their own normal distribution (the sampling distribution) which approaches a normal distribution as the sample size increases. <emphasis>The normal distribution has a
mean equal to the original mean multiplied by the sample size and a standard deviation
equal to the original standard deviation multiplied by the square root of the sample size.</emphasis>

</para><para id="element-7">The random variable <m:math><m:mo>Σ</m:mo>
<m:mi>X</m:mi></m:math> has the following z-score associated with it:</para><list id="element-434" list-type="labeled-item" mark-suffix="."><item><label>a</label><m:math><m:mi>Σx</m:mi></m:math>
is one sum.
</item>
